text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: "Needs washed" construction%0a:Author: aryans%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 05.04.2021 - 22:17%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-181002-92050#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 11:10-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-181002-92050#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA short introduction to the "needs washed" construction based on the Yale Grammatical Diversity Project%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe needs washed  construction is when the word "needs" is followed by a passive participle verb form like "washed", "fixed", or "cleaned". For example, %0a%0aYour shirt needs washed. %0aThe dryer needs repaired. %0a%0aThis construction isn't in Standard American English, where the same meanings as above would be communicated with the infinitive or gerund form of the verb:%0a%0aYour shirt needs to be washed. (infinitive)%0aThe dryer needs repairing. (gerund)%0a%0aThis construction, according to Murray and Simon (2002), is common in Western Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Ohio, and the Midwestern United States. It may have roots in Scots English. %0a%0aThe same construction can be applied to the words "wants" and "likes". Usually, if a passive participle verb form can be used with "needs", it can be used with "wants". If it can be used with "wants", it can be used with "likes". However, the converses do not necessarily hold. %0a%0aHere's an interesting syntactic property of this construction. If the "needs washed" construction is used with a negation, then the "need" must follow the negation, usually by inserting a "do" auxiliary verb. For example, the first construction is not acceptable, while the second is:%0a%0a*Your shirt needn't washed. %0aYour shirt don't need washed. %0a%0aSource: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/needs-washed%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
