diff:1617686249:1617686249:=1,64d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: "Needs washed" construction%0a%3c :Author: aryans%0a%3c :Section: B%0a%3c :Completed: 05.04.2021 - 22:17%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c A short introduction to the "needs washed" construction based on the Yale Grammatical Diversity Project%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c The needs washed  construction is when the word "needs" is followed by a passive participle verb form like "washed", "fixed", or "cleaned". For example, %0a%3c %0a%3c Your shirt needs washed. %0a%3c The dryer needs repaired. %0a%3c %0a%3c This construction isn't in Standard American English, where the same meanings as above would be communicated with the infinitive or gerund form of the verb:%0a%3c %0a%3c Your shirt needs to be washed. (infinitive)%0a%3c The dryer needs repairing. (gerund)%0a%3c %0a%3c This construction, according to Murray and Simon (2002), is common in Western Pennsylvania, West Virginia, Ohio, and the Midwestern United States. It may have roots in Scots English. %0a%3c %0a%3c The same construction can be applied to the words "wants" and "likes". Usually, if a passive participle verb form can be used with "needs", it can be used with "wants". If it can be used with "wants", it can be used with "likes". However, the converses do not necessarily hold. %0a%3c %0a%3c Here's an interesting syntactic property of this construction. If the "needs washed" construction is used with a negation, then the "need" must follow the negation, usually by inserting a "do" auxiliary verb. For example, the first construction is not acceptable, while the second is:%0a%3c %0a%3c *Your shirt needn't washed. %0a%3c Your shirt don't need washed. %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/needs-washed%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
